  OBSERVATION: H=7 is the ONLY gap in {1,3,5,7,9,11,13,15}!
  7 = 2³-1 = Φ₃(2)

  From h7_check_v3 data, H values at n=7 include:
  dc3=0: H=1
  dc3=1: H=3
  dc3=2: H=5 or 9
  dc3=3: H=9 or 15
  dc3=4: H=11,13,15,17
  dc3=5: H=15,19,23,25,27,29,31,33
  So H=7 is MISSING from all dc3 categories!

======================================================================
PART 4: THE IMPOSSIBILITY OF H = Φ₃(2)
======================================================================

  THEOREM CANDIDATE (HYP-1010): H = 7 = Φ₃(2) is never achievable
  for any tournament on any number of vertices n ≥ 3.

  PROOF SKETCH:
  H = 1 + 2α₁ + 4α₂ + 8α₃ + ... = 7
  → α₁ + 2α₂ + 4α₃ + ... = 3
  → (α₁, α₂, α₃, ...) ∈ {(3,0,0,...), (1,1,0,...)}
  (1,1,0,...) impossible: α₂ ≤ C(α₁,2) = 0.
  (3,0,0,...): need exactly 3 odd cycles, NO disjoint pair.

  CLAIM: For any tournament, 3 odd cycles with no disjoint pair
  force the existence of ADDITIONAL odd cycles.

  WHY: if 3 odd cycles all share a common vertex v,
  then the arcs among the other vertices are highly constrained.
  The constraint forces additional cycles beyond the original 3.

  At n=5: 3 three-cycles on 5 vertices sharing pairwise
  → forced 5-cycle (verified exhaustively)

  At n=7: 3 three-cycles sharing vertex 0
  → additional 3-cycles always appear (dc3 > 3)
  OR: dc3=3 but dc5 > 0 or dc7 > 0
  → α₁ > 3, so H > 7

  Checking all (dc3,dc5) with dc3+dc5=3 at n=5:
    (0,3): DOES NOT EXIST
    (1,2): DOES NOT EXIST
    (2,1): DOES NOT EXIST
    (3,0): DOES NOT EXIST

  Further analysis: WHY α₁=3 is impossible at n=5

  dc3=0 → transitive → dc5=0 → α₁=0
  dc3=1 → max dc5 at this dc3?
    dc3=0: max dc5 = 0
    dc3=1: max dc5 = 0
    dc3=2: max dc5 = 0
    dc3=3: max dc5 = 1
    dc3=4: max dc5 = 3
    dc3=5: max dc5 = 2

  So at n=5:
  dc3=0: dc5=0 → α₁=0
  dc3=1: max dc5=0 → max α₁=1
  dc3=2: max dc5=0 → max α₁=2
  dc3=4: max dc5=1 → max α₁=5 → JUMP!

  α₁=3 is SKIPPED! The jump from α₁=2 to α₁=4 happens because
  3 three-cycles at n=5 FORCE a 5-cycle (or more 3-cycles).
  This is why H=7 (= 1+2·3) is impossible!

  At n=7: dc3=3 gives H∈{9,15}.
  H=9 = 1+2·4 → α₁=4 (the 3 three-cycles force extra cycle)
  H=15 = 1+2·7 → α₁=7 (even more forced cycles)
  In both cases α₁ > 3, confirming the skip.

  RAMSEY-TYPE PHENOMENON:
  3 overlapping odd cycles → forced additional cycles
  This is analogous to R(3,3)=6: enough edges → forced triangle
  Here: enough overlapping cycles → forced extra cycles

======================================================================
PART 5: WHICH CYCLOTOMIC VALUES ARE H-GAPS?
======================================================================

  Φ_d(2) values and their H-achievability:
    Φ_d(2)   d  n=3  n=5
         1   1    ✓    ✓
         3   2    ✓    ✓
         7   3    ✗    ✗
         5   4    ✗    ✓
        31   5    ✗    ✗
         3   6    ✓    ✓
       127   7    ✗    ✗

  Φ₁(2) = 1: always achievable (transitive tournament)
  Φ₂(2) = 3: achievable (one 3-cycle, e.g. regular 3-tournament)
  Φ₃(2) = 7: NEVER achievable (gap at both n=5 and n=7)
  Φ₄(2) = 5: achievable (α₁=2)
  Φ₅(2) = 31: achievable at n=7 (from dc3=5 data)
  Φ₆(2) = 3: same as Φ₂
  Φ₇(2) = 127: beyond range for small n

  THE CYCLOTOMIC INTERPRETATION:
  Φ₃(x) = x²+x+1 with roots ω = e^{2πi/3}
  Φ₃(2) = 7: the 'third cyclotomic at 2'

  The 3 in Φ₃ corresponds to 3-CYCLES in tournaments.
  The evaluation at x=2 corresponds to the tournament KEY₁.
  The impossibility of H=Φ₃(2) is a STRUCTURAL constraint:
  3 entangled 3-cycles cannot avoid creating extra cycles.

  THIS IS THE TOURNAMENT ANALOG OF THE CUBE ROOT OF UNITY:
  Just as ω³=1 forces algebraic constraints,
  3 overlapping directed 3-cycles force cycle-count constraints.

Done.
